How can I overlay genetics data?

Genoppi allows for visualization of experimental proteomics data with

  • SNPs from genetic studies,
  • user uploaded genes (e.g. set of interesting genes from GTEx) to highlight corresponding proteins and
  • protein encoded by genes that are intolerant to loss-of-function mutations as determined by ExAC data


  1. SNP to gene mapping

Genoppi hosts pre-calculated pairwise measure of linkage disequilibrium (LD), which it uses to perform SNP-to-gene mapping using 1KG imputed single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) results.

User may provide a list of SNPs, found in 1000 Genomes Project, that are significantly associated to a trait of interest to the experiment as a text file in the following format with no column header:

The application will perform on-the-fly mapping of inputted SNPs to the 1KG genotypes and translate to a list of genes. For each CEU imputed SNP, genomic locus is defined as region containing r2>0.6 to the associated SNP within a 200-kb window; this region is then extended 50kb upstream and downstream. SNPs are mapped to candidate genes if the genomic coordinates of human protein-coding genes in hg19 overlap SNP loci.

If a SNP locus is a single-gene locus, the marker will be annotated as ‘SGL gene’ in the subsequent plot. If multiple protein-coding genes are present in SNP locus, all genes are mapped as candidate genes for the associated SNP and annotated as ‘MGL gene’ as shown below.




  1. Genes of interest

User must upload text file containing list(s) of corresponding protein’s genes in HGNC symbol for genes of interest mapping. First row of each column must contain the name describing the group of genes as shown below. There are no limits as to how many columns user may input.

User may upload input files for both SNP to gene mapping and highlighting genes of interest as well as provide a HGNC symbol for searching interaction partners in InWeb. Any combination of fields may be filled and resulting plot will highlight all relevant proteins from user inputted data.

If, in the case, the plot becomes too “busy,” user can choose to turn the labels off or turn off the markers by clicking on the legend you wish to hide.




  1. Intolerance to LoF mutations determined by ExAC data

If at any point user would like to identify proteins encoded by genes likely to be extremely intolerant to loss-of-function variation using the ExAC data, user can choose the color scheme “ExAC” on the side panel.
